# New session create with repo

`C-n` uses the current repo context when creating a new named session, so the new
session starts in that repo and records `@sesh.repo` metadata.

    :bins jj tmux

> [!NOTE]
> 'jj', and 'tmux' are available.

    :t rename-session -t 0 runner (success)
    :$ jj git init beta (exit: 0)
    :$ jj describe -R beta -m "beta commit" (exit: 0)
    :t new-session -d -s ui "sesh -r beta" (success)
    :t resize-window -t ui:0 -x 120 -y 10 (success)
    :pane ui:0.0

Select the discovered repo, set it as the current repo context, then create a
new session named `zeta`.

    :k beta C-r C-u zeta
    :snap "/\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2} \d{2}:\d{2}:\d{1,2}/t" "/(?:@|○|◆)\s+([a-z]{8})/w" "/\b([0-9a-f]{8})\b/h"

```terminal
session: zeta
  0/3 | [C-r] repo: beta | [C-n] new
                                                                                                                       ┃
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────






```
    :k C-n
    :snap -d 2s

```terminal
sh$























```

The client should switch to the new session, and the session should carry the
selected repo metadata.

    :t display-message -p '#{client_session}' (success)

```
zeta
```
    :t list-sessions -F '#{session_name}:#{@sesh.repo}' (success)

```
runner:
zeta:beta
```

